Rating: 4
Here are the changes I made, on the suggestions of other reviewers: 1. Used only one onion but added two finely chopped shallots and one finely chopped bulb of fennel. 2. Reduced the pepper flakes to 1/4-1/2 tsp and passed additional pepper flakes at the table for those who like this spicier. 3. Subbed white wine (pinot grigio) for the red. 4. Used a yellow bell pepper in place of the green. 5. Used the following seafood: mahi mahi, clams, mussels, shrimp. Oh, and I just threw those in in the following order, to cook over about 8-10 minutes: clams, mussels, fish, shrimp. Worked out great, no need to remove the shellfish before proceeding with the rest. While we didn't use crab which means I didn't technically make cioppino, this was delicious and I would make it again in a second! The friends I cooked for raved. We are in a gluten-free house so served it over rice with some homemade GF focaccia on the side to soak up the juices. The bread on the side to soak up the juices is necessary! Don't skip it!

Rating: 4
This is a great recipe. Like others, I also prefer to substitute white wine and fish stock for the red wine/clam juice/chicken broth, and I add one finely chopped medium fennel bulb with the onions and garlic. I also top each bowl with a couple of slices of grilled croutons made from crusty bread brushed with olive oil. Oh, and a generous drizzle of this rouille: http://www.epicurious.com/recipes/food/views/Rouille-105637 The rouille is more traditional with bouillabaisse, but it makes a really tasty addition to cioppino, too.

