Rating: 3
Nice recipe! Since I prefer more of a brothy soup, I strained the tomoatoes and onions etc into a saucepan. I also sauted some fennel till it was soft and put it aside keeping the flavor from in the pan. I added saffron to the broth and then added the seafood. One word of caution...Getting all the seafood to be at its optimal doneness is tough. You may want to cook the seafood on the side (except clams or mussels), then add to the sauce just to warm.

Rating: 4
This is wonderful and one of the few 4 stars I've given out over the years on this website. I incorporated various excellent suggestions by previous reviewers including: adding some diced fennel, celery and leeks (reducing the onion to 1 med-large onion); substituting yellow bell pepper for green; adding a pinch of saffron; adding an extra bottle of clam juice, using combination of red/white wine (although either would be fine); adding a heaping tablespoon of fresh oregano and fresh thyme. For the tomatoes, I used a 28 can of whole tomatoes from San Marzano region (worth every penny), a box of extra sauce (I use Pomi in a box), and a few diced fresh tomatoes I had lying around. For the seafood, I added halibut cheeks, Alaska clams, Blue mussells, scallops, shrimp and 2 pounds of Red King Crab (huge ones available at Costco for $13.99 per pound - biggest I've seen this season). This was very impressive served in large shallow white bowls. Great served with herb/parmesan focaccia bread, tossed salad with butter lettuce and burgandy/herb dressing and a great Oregon Pinot Noir. Make this recipe - it's worth the $$$. Also, I highly recommend making the broth/sauce the day before. The flavors really meld together. YUM!!!

